<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Managing Missions
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        How to add, edit, template, delete, and configure mission entries in a storyboard file.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Missions Tab
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Missions are the individual playable entries that appear under districts on the overworld map. To begin adding missions, select the <Bold>Missions</Bold> tab in the management bar.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Storyboard%20Editor;component/Help/Images/storyboard_missions_tab.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph>
        The Missions tab includes four main buttons:
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Add</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Adds a single mission entry to the list.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Edit</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Opens the selected mission in the Edit Mission box.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Delete</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Deletes the selected mission entry.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Template</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Creates ten mission entries at once for faster setup.</Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Using the Mission Template
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Template</Bold> button creates ten mission entries at a time. This is useful when creating a new storyboard and saves time compared with adding every mission manually.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The template also styles mission IDs in a way that works properly with the Urban Chaos executable. Some mission IDs and mission names are hardcoded to open in a specific sequence, so the template avoids those problem areas and creates a linear unlock structure.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Storyboard%20Editor;component/Help/Images/storyboard_missions_template_button.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Note:</Run>
                <Run>For custom storyboards, the template workflow is recommended because it avoids known executable limitations around certain mission IDs and names.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Adding a Mission
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To add a single mission, click the <Bold>Add</Bold> button. A new mission entry appears in the mission list.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        To edit the new mission, highlight it and press <Bold>Edit</Bold>, or double-click it in the list. This opens the <Bold>Edit Mission</Bold> box.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Storyboard%20Editor;component/Help/Images/storyboard_missions_add_button.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Storyboard%20Editor;component/Help/Images/storyboard_missions_edit_window.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Edit Mission Fields
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Edit Mission box contains the key values that define how the mission appears and how it is unlocked.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Mission ID</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">The mission ID is automatically assigned. Custom mission IDs start at <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">14</Run> to avoid known issues with earlier hardcoded mission IDs.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Name</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">The mission name shown on the map, such as <Bold>Urban Shakedown</Bold>.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">File</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">The actual mission file that should open, such as <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">police1.ucm</Run>.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">District ID</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">The district ID that the mission should appear under. For example, if the newly added district is <Bold>District 2</Bold>, enter <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">2</Run> to place the mission under that district.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Unlocked By</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">The mission ID that must be completed before this mission becomes available. Setting this value to <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">1</Run> makes the mission available from the beginning.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Type</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Can be set to <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">0</Run> or <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">1</Run>. This currently has no known effect.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Flags</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Can be set to <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">0</Run> or <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">1</Run>. This currently has no known effect.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Audio File</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">The briefing audio file associated with the mission. These have been mapped to the mission IDs as laid out in the source code. For example, the first custom mission, <Bold>Mission ID 14</Bold>, corresponds to <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">policem4.wav</Run>.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Briefing</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">The briefing text shown alongside the audio before the mission is accepted.</Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Tip:</Run>
                <Run>For a first mission in a new custom sequence, set Unlocked By to 1 so the mission is available from the beginning.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Saving a Mission
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Fill out the mission fields as required, then press <Bold>OK</Bold>. The mission entry is saved and appears under the district specified by its District ID.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Storyboard%20Editor;component/Help/Images/storyboard_missions_saved_under_district.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Deleting a Mission
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To delete a mission, highlight it in the Missions list and press the <Bold>Delete</Bold> button.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Storyboard%20Editor;component/Help/Images/storyboard_missions_delete_button.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">⚠ Important:</Run>
                <Run>Deleting a mission may affect other missions that use its ID in the Unlocked By field. Check mission unlock chains before saving.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Basic Mission Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create at least one district first.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Open the <Bold>Missions</Bold> tab.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Use <Bold>Add</Bold> for one mission or <Bold>Template</Bold> to create ten missions at once.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Double-click a mission or press <Bold>Edit</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the mission name, file, district ID, unlock value, audio file, and briefing text.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Press <Bold>OK</Bold> to save the mission.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Check the district marker on the map to confirm the mission appears under the correct district.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Next Steps
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        After creating districts and missions, continue to <Bold>Export</Bold> to save the finished storyboard as a game-ready <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">urban.sty</Run> file.
    </Paragraph>

</FlowDocument>
